(NOTE: if the board above correctly displays, but you canРђЎt imagine playing a game based in such alien characters, rest assured that the Shgoi implementation over at SGGS also supports a РђюlatinРђЮ mode, using РђюfriendlierРђЮ ASCII names, in addition to the (default) РђюkanjiРђЮ display mode shown above.)

## The Problem

By default, Lagrange does not include glyphs for any CJK characters (~kanji). No problem, because the website _does_ provide them, along with symbols for many other useful characters, via any of the Noto Sans fontpacks. (Lagrange's РђюManage Fonts...РђЮ page provides a link directly to those fontpacks, via a РђюDownload new fontsРђЮ link at the top of that page.)

However, the Shogi board above still was not displaying correctly for me in Lagrange, even after installing Lagrange's notosans-set.fontpack. Why? Well, the fonts contained in that fontpack are not designated as monospace, and so are not used within preformatted text... except as РђюbackupsРђЮ to supply any missing characters that the default monospace font (Iosevka) does not have.

As mentioned earlier, an easy fix is to use SGGS's РђюlatinРђЮ mode for displaying the Shogi board. However, as I have a real Shogi set at home, IРђЎm more accustomed to identifying and reasoning about the pieces by their kanji designations, so I was reluctant to use latin mode. I was working around the issue by using a terminal Gemini client (AmforaРђћvery nice!) instead.

## Finding the Solution

I went out and found a Noto Sans Mono CJK set of truetype fonts, and thought that would solve things for me. Turns out, no, because the fonts I got are not, in fact, monospace. Among other things, РђюvРђЮ and Рђю^РђЮ (both ASCII characters) have different widths. So thatРђЎs clearly not going to help.

So, I went hunting for free, monospaced CJK fonts. I had to give -Noto to Google, because search results were full of Noto Sans Mono CJK, but I had already ruled those out. I happened across Kurinto, in OpenSUSEРђЎs Fontinfo site, downloaded, verified it in LibreOffice, created the fontpack, and verified it in Lagrange. Phew! Finally, I have a solution.
=> https://fontinfo.opensuse.org/fonts/KurintoMonoCJKRegular.html OpenSUSE Fontinfo site (Kurinto Mono CJK font page)


